gomodel:SYNGO_2185  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Olfm1 is a secreted glycoprotein that interacts with GluA2-containing AMPA receptors on synaptic membranes. Biochemical fractionation from adult mouse cortex and retina shows Olfm1 co-purifies with synaptic membrane fractions but not synaptic cytosol in both tissues (Figure 6A). Co-immunoprecipitation experiments from synaptic membranes purified from mouse cortex shows Olfm1 localizes to a protein complex containing Olfm2, GluA2 and PSD-95 (Figure 6D-F).. Experimental description: Subcellular fractionation, Western blot and immunoprecipitation: The cerebral cortex and retina (n= 5) were isolated from WT mice\n\nMice information from methods section: All animals used in the experiments were managed according to the ARVO statement for the use of animals in ophthalmic and vision research.\nAll experiments using animalswere approved by the NEI AnimalCare and Use Committee. Olfm1 mutant mice have been reported previously (Cheng et al., 2007;Nakaya et al., 2013). A mouse line in which the cre expression is under the control of regulatory sequences of the mouse zona pellucida 3 gene promoter (ZP3-cre) (Lewandoski et al., 1997)was\nobtained from the Jackson laboratory. Generation and characterization of Olfm2 KO mice\nOlfm2 KO (Olfm2-KO) mice were generated by deleting exons 2-6 of the Olfm2 gene. A BAC clone containing mouse Olfm2 locus was obtained from Geneservices (Cambridge, UK) and was used to construct a targeting vector in which exons 2-6 were replaced with the LacZ gene\n(β-galactosidase or β-gal)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5676-366X" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9783-5183" ;
        dc:date           "2018-01-24" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_2185" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

